occurrences.line_text: By whose aduise old Priams cittie fell,
Thence brought th[m] to the second roome, whose wals
Whose noble deedes aboue the Northerne starre
Whose father Hercules in Fraunce did quell,
Whose wanton pleasures him too much did please.
Whose footsteps Bladud following in arts
Whose simple answere, wanting colours faire
In whose sad time bloud did from heauen raine:
Whose death t'auenge, his mother mercilesse,
Whose countreis he redus'd to quiet state,
He had two sonnes, whose eldest called Lud
The weary Britons, whose war-hable youth
Whose dolefull moniments who list to rew,
A bridge of bras, whose sound heaue[n]s thunder seem'd to bee.
Whose emptie place the mightie Oberon
Whose hideous shapes were like to feends of hell,
That like a ghost he seem'd, whose graue-clothes were vnbound.
Of mightie Magnes stone, whose craggie clift
On whose sharpe clifts the ribs of vessels broke,
For spoyle of wretches, whose vnhappie cace,
Whose mariners and merchants with much toyle,
Whose circled waters rapt with whirling sway,
Strowed with pleasauns, whose faire grassy ground
Whose bounches hanging downe, seemed to entice
Whose sappy liquor, that with fulnesse sweld,
Whose depth exceeded not three cubits hight,
Whose sleepie head she in her lap did soft dispose.
His fomy steed, whose fierie feete did burne
Whose image she had seene in Venus looking glas.
Whose hideous horror and sad trembling sound
Whose face did seeme as cleare as Christall stone,
The whiles faire Britomart, whose constant mind,
For whose deare sake full many a bitter stownd,
Whose soueraine beautie hath no liuing pere,
Into an inner rowme, whose royaltee
From chase of greater beasts, whose brutish pryde
Faire Malecasta, whose engrieued spright
Be thou faire Britomart, whose prayse I write,
O soueraigne Queene, whose prayse I would endite,
Whose prowesse paragon saw neuer liuing wight.
Whose root and stalke so bitter yet did tast,
Whose vertues through the wyde world soone were solemniz'd.
Through whose bright ventayle lifted vp on hye
Her aged Nurse, whose name was Glauce hight,
Nor Prince, nor pere it is, whose loue hath gryde
Whose shape or person yet I neuer saw,
From whose two loynes thou afterwards did rayse
Whose big embodied braunches shall not lin,
Whose brother Oswin, daunted with like dread,
Whose Empire lenger here, then euer any stood.
Whose future woes so plaine he fashioned,
For Rhodoricke, whose surname shalbe Great,
Whose clawes were newly dipt in cruddy blood,
The bold Bunduca, whose victorious
Whose lignage from this Lady I deriue along.
Of whose foule outrage they impatient,
Whose chaunce it was, that soone he did repent,
Whose like in Faery lond were seldome seene,
Like as a ship, whose Lodestarre suddenly
The baser wit, whose idle thoughts alway
In whose faire eyes, like lamps of quenched fire,
We mortall wights, whose liues and fortunes bee
In whose enclosed shadow there was pight
More deare then life she tendered, whose flowre
Faire ympes of beautie, whose bright shining beames
By Stygian lake I vow, whose sad annoy
There stood a stately Mount, on whose round top
Whose shadie boughes sharpe steele did neuer lop,
Sad Amaranthus, in whose purple gore
A litle smoke, whose vapour thin and light,
Whose sides empurpled were with smiling red,
How she might heale her sonne, whose senses were decayd.
Whose like on earth was neuer framed yit,
Whose trampling feet vpon the hollow lay
Whose beauty doth her bounty far surpasse,
Where proud Encelade, whose wide nosethrils burnd
She sent at him one firie dart, whose hed
Whose fruitlesse liues were vnder furrow sowne,
Against that nation, from whose race of old
Vpon whose stubborne neck, whereat he raues
By Sanglamort my sword, whose deadly dent
Ah gentle knight, whose deepe conceiued griefe
Like a discolourd Snake, whose hidden snares
Whose hideous tayle his left foot did enfold,
Ensewd, whose noyance fild the fearefull sted,
Of persons flockt, whose names is hard to read:
Whose names and natures I note readen well;
Saue that same woefull Ladie, both whose hands
And to him said, Thou wicked man, whose meed
But most faire Amoret, whose gentle spright
And to him cald; whose voices knowen sound
Whose too long absence him had sore annoyd,
In whose chast breast all bountie naturall,
The deare compassion of whose bitter fit
Whose chiefe desire is loue and friendly aid
I saw (quoth she) a stranger knight, whose name
Whose Lord hath done my loue this foule despight?
Is wicked discord, whose small sparkes once blowen
The snowy Florimell, whose beautie bright
Which when as Blandamour, whose fancie light
Whose scoffed words he taking halfe in scorne,
Whose like aliue on earth he weened not:
Assembled were, to weet whose she should bee,
Her name was Agape whose children werne
Most wretched men, whose dayes depend on thrids so vaine.
Like an old Oke whose pith and sap is seare,
As one whose inner parts had bene ythrild
And next to Cambell, whose sad ruefull cheare
Whose sharpe prouokement them incenst so sore,
Whose beautie each of them thought excellent,
Vnto whose rescue forth rode Paridell;
Whose luckelesse riders late were ouerthrowen;
Whose beauties beame eftsoones did shine so bright,
Whose face discouered, plainely did expresse
For that strange Dame, whose beauties wonderment
The gentle Scudamour, whose hart whileare
Whose raging rigour neither steele nor bras
Whose fire were better turn'd to other flame;
But Scudamour whose hart twixt doubtfull feare
The louely Amoret, whose gentle hart
Whose knottie snags were sharpned all afore,
Vnhappy mayd (then answerd she) whose dread
Whose cursed vsage and vngodly trade
Whose bodies chast, when euer in his powre
But like a ghastly Gelt, whose wits are reaued,
Whose tender heart the faire Belphebe had,
For he whose daies in wilfull woe are worne,
Whose bloudie corse they shew'd him there beside,
Whose looser thought will lightly be misled,
Whose noble kind at first was sure of heauenly seed.
Whose steadie hand was faine his steede to guyde,
And what he was, whose eyes did flame with fire;
But she, whose hart to loue was wholly lent,
For whose sole libertie I loue and life did stake.
Him selfe, whose minde did trauell as with chylde,
Whose will her weakenesse could no way represse,
Whose like they neuer saw till that same houre:
Whose dangerous successe depended yet in dout.
At whose request he gan him selfe aduise
Whose right she is, where euer she be straide,
To take on him that paine: whose great desire
Whose office was, against all manner wights
The shield of Loue, whose guerdon me hath graced,
Vnto whose trust the charge thereof was lent:
Or did misdoubt some ill, whose cause did not appeare.
Whose manner was all passengers to stay,
Whose smallest minute lost, no riches render may.
The Gate of good desert, whose goodly pride
Whose liues although decay'd, yet loues decayed neuer.
Whose goodly workmanship farre past all other
Whose hight all Ephesus did ouersee,
Whose substance was vneath to vnderstand:
Were with a snake, whose head & tail were fast co[m]byned.
Whose shapes seem'd not like to terrestriall boyes,
Whose luring baytes oftimes doe heedlesse harts entyse.
Whose eyes like twinkling stars in euening cleare,
Whose yuorie shoulders weren couered all,
Long Rhodanus, whose sourse springs from the skie;
And Tygris fierce, whose streames of none may be withstood.
And the still Darent, in whose waters cleane
Through both whose borders swiftly downe it glides,
Whose like none else could shew, the which they Ruffins call.
Next these came Tyne, along whose stony bancke
Whose bad condition yet it doth retaine,
And Mulla mine, whose waues I whilom taught to weep.
The next, the stubborne Newre, whose waters gray
With many more, whose names no tongue can tell.
Whose fruitfull seede farre passeth those in land,
Whose names and nations were too long to tell,
Like as an Hynde whose calfe is falne vnwares
Whose soueraine powre is herein most exprest,
Whose glorie is to aide all suppliants pore,
With a fayre loue, whose losse I now do rew,
But he, whose spirit was with pride vpblowne,
Whose scalp is bare, that bondage doth bewray,
High God, whose goodnesse he despaired quight,
Whose waters with his filthy bloud it stayned:
In whose right hands great power is contayned,
Whose great assembly they did much admire,
Of all whose weight, he would not misse a fether.
Whose counsels depth thou canst not vnderstand,
To Marinell, whose name the Heralds loud resounded.
Came to the open hall, to listen whose
Whose voice so soone as he did vndertake,
And knights of Maidenhead, whose praise she would empaire.
Whose other wing, now made vnmeete for flight,
Whose presence all their troups so much encombred
Many braue knights, whose names right well he knew,
Whose wandring fancie after lust did raunge,
Vnhappie Knight, vpon whose hopelesse state
Whose hidden drift he could not well perceiue;
Chiefely by him, whose life her law doth bynd,
Whose life did lie in her least eye-lids fall;
Whose character in th'Adamantine mould
Whose life and manners straunge she neuer knew;
Like as a wayward childe, whose sounder sleepe
His name was Guizor, whose vntimely fate
Vnto whose temple when as Britomart
Whose goodly building when she did behould,
Whose like before she neuer saw nor red;
The fruitfull vine, whose liquor blouddy red
Each of whose lockes did match a man in might,
By whose entreatie both they ouercommen,
Whose top was arm'd with many an yron hooke,
Whose porch, that most magnificke did appeare,
Some one, whose tongue was for his trespasse vyle
Whose skirts were bordred with bright sunny beams,
Whose long rest rusted the bright steely brand;
But she, whose Princely breast was touched nere
Whose dreadfull shape was neuer seene of none
Whose grudging ghost was thereout fled and past,
As by sad Belge seemes, whose wrongs though long
Whose vgly shape none euer saw, nor kend,
A Dragons taile, whose sting without redresse
To see the man, whose euerlasting praise
From whose sterne presence they diffused ran,
Whose goodly light then Phebus lampe doth shine more cleare?
Whose steale was yron studded, but not long,
Whose nature is to grieue, and grudge at all,
Whose sight to her is greatest crosse, may fall,
In whose pure minde, as in a mirrour sheene
And for this Mayd, whose party thou doest take,
Like as a water streame, whose swelling sourse
The heauy burden of whose dreadfull might
Whose euery act and word, that he did say,
Whose fellow he before had sent apart;
I whose vnryper yeares are yet vnfit
After whose death, his brother seeing mee
Whose gealous dread induring not a peare,
To whose wise read she hearkning, sent me streight
Doth fall, whose like hereafter seldome may,
Like as a flowre, whose silken leaues small,
At whose calamity, for more despight
And that this Lady, both whose sides are pearst
Whose vertue he by vse well vnderstood:
To Calepine, whose eares those shrieches shrill
Whose burden mote empeach his needfull speed,
That of the like, whose linage was vnknowne,
He came, whose couert stopt his further sight,
Had giuen them, whose griefe through suffraunce sore increast.
Cruell Typhaon, whose tempestuous rage
Of these poore folk, whose soules with black dishonor
On which the first, whose force her first doth bring,
That recreant knight, whose hated life I sought?
Whose cruell handling when that Squire beheld,
A saluage Bull, whose cruell hornes doe threat
Y e gentle Ladies, in whose soueraine powre
Whose doome was death, but lightly slipping by,
Whose share, her guiltlesse bloud they would present,
Her goodly thighes, whose glorie did appeare
Whose siluer lockes bedeckt his beard and hed,
And this sweet peace, whose lacke did then appeare.
Whose sensefull words empierst his hart so neare,
With grace from her, whose loue his heart hath sore engrieued.
Vnto a place, whose pleasaunce did appere
Whose sundry parts were here too long to tell:
Whose like before his eye had neuer seene,
Tell, me what were they all, whose lacke thee grieues so sore.
And also of the place, whose pleasures rare
Faire Pastorella, whose sad mournefull hew
Withouten her, whose worth aboue all threasure
Whose whelpes are stolne away, she being otherwhere.
Whose heauy tydings now I haue to tell.
To her, whose name he often did repeat;
But he, whose hart through feare was late fordonne,
Do seize vpon some beast, whose flesh is bare,
Whose course is often stayd, yet neuer is astray.
Her name was Claribell: whose father hight
But she whose sides before with secret wound
Whose like he neuer once did speake, nor heare,
Straunge bands, whose like till then he neuer bore,
But whosoeuer once hath fastened
But whosoeuer contrarie doth proue,
To pluck it out with pincers firie whot,
Neither to melt in pleasures whot desire,
He soone approched, panting, breathlesse, whot,
Nath'lesse now quench thy whot emboyling wrath:
And his whot fire burnes in mine entrails bright,
From their whot worke they did themselues withdraw
Coles of contention and whot vengeance tynd.
Vpon a mighty furnace, burning whot,
More whot, then Aetn', or flaming Mongiball:
Now seeming flaming whot, now stony cold.
Of his sharpe darts and whot artillerie;
So whot she burned in that lustfull fyre,
And cruell blades yet steeming with whot bloud,
One day, as she to shunne the season whot,
Ne ought the water cooled their whot bloud,
Might lightly fetch. But he was fierce and whot,
And inly burnt with flames most raging whot,
How many flyes in whottest sommers day
Why Dame (quoth he) what hath ye thus dismayd?
As the God of my life? why hath he me abhord?
And sooth to say, why I left you so long,
And said, Why Archimago, lucklesse syre,
Why they were come, her royall state to see,
Why dame (quoth he) what oddes can euer bee,
Why suffredst thou thy Nephewes deare to fall
Why fearest thou, that canst not hope for thing,
Why do ye lenger feed on loathed light,
Why wilt not let him passe, that long hath stood
Whe[n] houre of death is come, let none aske whence, nor why.
Why then doest thou, O man of sin, desire
Why shouldst thou then despeire, that chosen art?
O foolish men, why haste ye to your owne decay?
Much more then that, why they in bands were layd,
But now aread, old father, why of late
Why then should witlesse man so much misweene
Or why should euer I henceforth desire,
Sir Guyon, why with so fierce saliaunce,
Why liuest thou, dead dog, a lenger day,
Why then dost thou, Ã´ man, that of them all
Then Mammon wexing wroth, And why then, said,
Why takest not of that same fruit of gold,
O why should heauenly God to man haue such regard?
For why should a dead dog be deckt in armour bright?
Why should not that dead carrion satisfie
After so wicked deed why liu'st thou lenger day?
To weet why on your shield so goodly scord
Gentle Madame, why beene ye thus dismaid,
Till Alma him bespake, Why wonder yee
She woxe; yet wist she neither how, nor why,
Or why make ye such Monster of your mind?
Into her former fit; for why, no powre
Why do thy cruell billowes beat so strong,
Gan them informe the cause, why that same dore
The cause, why Satyrane and Paridell
That is the cause, why neuer any knight
But why do we deuise of others ill,
Gan causen, why she could not come in place;
False loue, why do men say, thou canst not see,
Why then is Amoret in caytiue band,
Why then is Busirane with wicked hand
His owne deare mother, (ah why should he so?)
Why do ye striue for Ladies loue so sore,
Vile hag (sayd Scudamour) why dost thou lye?
I saw, why should I doubt to tell the same?
Why doth mine hand from thine auenge abstaine,
Why do I not it wreake, on thee now in my might?
Sir knight why ride ye dumpish thus behind,
O   Why doe wretched men so much desire,
The cause why she was couered with a vele,
Why should they not likewise in loue agree,
But all in vaine: for why he found no way
And why? doe it declare vnto me trew.
For why, he sayd they all vnequall were,
Ne euer any asketh reason why.
Then why doest not, thou ill aduized man,
But why haue ye (said Artegall) forborne
Why then will ye, fond Dame, attempted bee
Why hath thy hand too bold it selfe embrewed
But all in vaine; for why, no remedy
Why haue ye me alone thus long yleft?
Or deare aby, for why his Lord of old
But why when I them saw, fled they away from me?
Ye both forwearied be: therefore a whyle
Both eyes and hart attonce, during the whyle
Where I with sound of trompe will also rest a whyle.
To graunt vnto those warriours truce a whyle;
One while she blam'd her selfe; another whyle
My life now to, for which a little whyle
That from her self vnwares he might her steale the whyle.
That cursed wight, from whom I scapt whyleare,
And turning to that place, in which whyleare
In Mammons house, the Palmer, whom whyleare
To be auenged of that shot whyleare:
Their wofull harts he wounded had whyleare,
Did seeme to be the same, which she escapt whyleare.
He came, which full of guests he found whyleare,
I found her not, where I her left whyleare,
Whyleare by Tryphon was not throughly healed,
Whom hauing lost (as ye haue heard whyleare)
After long sorrowes suffered whyleare,
The which whyleare she was so greedily
Those warlike armes, which Calepine whyleare
And with him eke the saluage, that whyleare
From Meliboe and from themselues whyleare,
Out of the flames, which he had quencht whylere
From whom the Squire of Dames was reft whylere;
I will the truth discouer, as it chaunst whylere.
That they were poore heardgroomes, the which whylere
But foolish Mayd, whyles heedlesse of the hooke,
The whyles Sir Artegall, with that old knight
For all that night, the whyles the Prince did rest
The whyles they strike at him with heedlesse might,
The whyles his saluage page, that wont be prest,
The whyles his Lord in siluer slomber lay,
The whyles she wayld, the more they did reioyce.
The whyles their beasts there in the budded broomes
Her whyles Sir Calidore there vewed well,
Whylest there the varlet stood, he saw from farre
It fortun'd whylest they were thus ill beset,
Thus there he stood, whylest high ouer his head,
Whylest kings and kesars at her feet did them prostrate.
Whylest vnderneath her feete, there as she sate,
Whylest he of none was stopped, nor withstood.
And whylest an Infant from a Beare
Whylest euery ioynt for dread of death did quake,
Effect the same, whylest all the night was spent.
Whylest time did offer meanes him sleeping to surprize.
Thus whylest they were debating diuerslie,
Whylest she, the Ladie of her libertie,
Whylest euerie one with helping hands did striue
Whylest thus he talkt, the knight with greedy eare
The whylest at pleasure she mote sport and play;
Whylest thus she in these hellish dens remayned,
Whom whylest she did with watrie eyne behold,
With Claribell, whylest he that monster sought
For in that court whylome her well they knew:
That whylome was to me too dearely deare.
It Merlin was, which whylome did excell
Whylome, before that cursed Dragon got
Who dying whylome did diuide this fort
Of whom high Ioue wont whylome feasted bee,
Not that, which antique Cadmus whylome built
Foreby the Riuer, that whylome was hight
As th'Isle of Delos whylome men report
Whylome her louers, which her lusts did feed,
That whylome in diuinest wits did raine,
Their puissance, whylome full dernely tryde:
There the wise Merlin whylome wont (they say)
(This Liagore whylome had learned skill
Sith her whylome vpon high Pindus hill,
Whylome to haunt, but there she found him not;
Whylome as antique stories tellen vs,
That whylome wont to be the victors meed;
Her husband Vulcan whylome for her sake,
(Whylome for ventrous Knights the bedding best)
That whylome in your minde wont to despise them all.
For whylome they haue conquerd sea and land,
Which being whylome launcht with louely dart,
As whylome was the custome ancient
So whylome didst thou to faire Florimell;
Of an huge Geauntesse whylome was bred;
Against the Titans, that whylome rebelled
Therefore whylome to knights of great emprise
With which whylome he gotten had great fame:
That whylome hath of Hercules bene told,
Of th'old ï¿½gyptian Kings, that whylome were;
So whylome learnd that mighty Iewish swaine,
That whylome wont to doe so many quake,
For she whylome (as ye mote yet right well
He that whylome in Spaine so sore was dred,
The which whylome that Ladies owne had bene;
For whylome he had bene a doughty Knight,
Who whylome was in his youthes freshest flowre
Like as whylome that strong Tirynthian swaine,
That he, wich earst them combatted, was Guyon bold.
In wich the names of all loues folke were fyled,
That soone to loose her wicked bands did her constraine.
In which that wicked wight his dayes doth weare:
Bathed in wanton blis and wicked ioy:
Came to their wicked maister, and gan tell
That here wex old in sleepe, whiles wicked wights
The wicked witch now seeing all this while
With wicked herbes and ointments did besmeare
For of his wicked pelfe his God he made,
The wicked witch, saying; In that faire face
Her wicked dayes with wretched knife did end,
Through wicked pride, and wasted wealthes decay.
Ne let that wicked woman scape away;
And loe that wicked woman in your sight,
Ere long they come, where that same wicked wight
Greeu'd with remembrance of his wicked wayes,
Who by her wicked arts, and wylie skill,
Vnwares me wrought vnto her wicked will,
Ne wicked enuie, ne vile gealosy
He gan to weaue a web of wicked guile,
Of grieuous mischiefes, which a wicked Fay
And him behind, a wicked Hag did stalke,
Where this same wicked villein did me light vpon.
Most wretched woman, and of wicked race,
And wicked doome, to Iewes despiteous
To serue to wicked man, to serue his wicked foe.
To serue to wicked man, to serue his wicked foe.
After so wicked deed why liu'st thou lenger day?
But read what wicked hand hath robbed mee
Of false Acrasia, and her wicked wiles,
As if the rest some wicked hand did rend,
The wicked Gobbelines in bloudy field:
That wicked band of villeins fresh begon
Their wicked engins they against it bent:
And euermore their wicked Capitaine
There follow'd fast at hand two wicked Hags,
His wicked arrowes, gathered them againe,
Which when those wicked Hags from farre did spy,
So riu'd her trembling hart, and wicked end did make.
By that same wicked witch, to worke vs dreed,
And with their wicked wings them oft did smight,
Emongst the Roses grow some wicked weeds;
Then doth this wicked euill thee infest,
And to their purpose vsed wicked art:
So was their fortune good, though wicked were their mind.
But wicked fortune mine, though mind be good,
Ne shall auaile the wicked sorcery
The wicked steele through his left side did glaunce;
After that wicked foster fiercely went.
His wicked fortune, that had turnd aslope,
The wicked steele stayd not, till it did light
Where wicked ghosts do waile their former sin.
